<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-179-224  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 179 224.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  April 11 1989 v3 n15 p8(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT MacWEEK Inc. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Disinfectant to be upgraded. (antiviral program)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Brower, Emily.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Product:   Disinfectant (Utility program).andO;Topic:     Computer VirusesSecurity SoftwareUpgradingPublic Software.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Disinfectant to be upgradedandM;The creators of Disinfectant, a new shareware anti-virus program releasedlate last month, have already announced plans for an upgrade to fix severalbugs.andM;John Norstad, Disinfectant's primary programmer, said the upgrade will beavailable in two to three weeks.andP;  Disinfectant 1.0 detects and removesSCORES, nVir A, nVir B, Hpat, AIDS, ANTI, INIT29 and viruses based on theMacMAG virus.andP;  Version 1.1 will fix several bugs, including an inability toscan non-local disks on a TOPS network and problems scanning active serverdisks.andM;Norstad and MacMash, an international virus study group meetingelectronically on Internet, wrote Disinfectant to aid virus victims whocannot afford commercial anti-virus software.andM;&quot;We felt there was a need for something free, especially for universities.andO;Site licenses are too expensive; they take too large a chunk out of adepartment's software budget,&quot; said Norstad, who works as a systems analystfor Northwestern University in Evanston, Ill.andM;Norstad said he and his fellow Mac programmers plan to support Disinfectantthrough communications and cooperative programming over Internet.andO;Disinfectant is electronically distributed on CompuServe, Bix, GEnie andDelphi.andO;</TEXT></DOC>